title: Impressora 3d caseira  - #1 Apresentação da Ramps 1.4 shield
description:
*Loja → https://shopee.com.br/kilovolt_
*Instagram → https://www.instagram.com/autonomia_digital/

Fala ae galera, estou começando a montar a minha impressora 3D caseira, tomando como partida alguns tutoriais da internet e vou compartilhar com vocês como será feita a minha e passar como irei montar, peças e etc... 
Nesse primeiro vídeo quero apenas passar para vocês um pequeno conhecimento sobre a ramps 1.4 que será nosso shield para controlar os motores sendo todo o sistema controlado pelo arduino mega 2560. 

*Lembrando que é meu primeiro contato com esse mundo

title: Impressora 3d caseira  - #2 Marlin - Configuração impressora 3d

title: Impressora 3D Simples | Parte 1 | Como fazer uma impressora 3D mais barata do que a impressora comum
description:
Projeto BT4
Impressora 3D simples
Volume de impressão: 140x130x100 (comprimento x largura x altura em mm)

Arquivos:

https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/0B69KEXPVHfbSMl9Rc2d6U1J4ZGM?usp=sharing

Quanto custa uma Impressora 3D?
Alguns exemplos.

As impressoras comuns são bem mais baratas.
A produção em larga escala reduz o custo.

Quanto custa uma impressora auto-replicável?
As peças plásticas são caras.

E fazer uma impressora simples?
Bem básica.

É possível fazer uma impressora 3D pelo custo de uma impressora comum?
Por exemplo, usando peças padrões e adaptando o motor.

Lista de peças.
Custo estimado $50.

Este é o projeto BT4.

title: IMPRESSORA 3D CASEIRA. Muito simples.
description:
PEÇAS PRINCIPAIS INSUBSTITUÍVEIS.

12 Rolamentos Lm8uu R$63,99 (Mercado livre)
1 Acoplamento Flexível 5mm*8mm R$ 15,90 (Mercado Livre)
3 polias mais 2 metros de correia GT2 R$ 49,90 (Mercado Livre)
3 Endstop R$30,00 (Mercado livre)
kit hotend + 2 MK8 + 5 bicos 0,5 R$ 139,00 (Mercado Livre)
1 Mesa aquecida + 1 Placa de controle 3D LCD Full graphics R$ 81,62(Banggood)
2 Eixo retificado 8mm fresa 1M Cada R$ 48,00 (Mercado Livre)
1 Tubo ptfe 1M R$7,99 (Mercado Livre)
1 Fonte 12V 30A 360W R$ 46,89 (Mercado Livre)
1 Fuso T8 + Castanha bronze R$ 72,00 (Mercado Livre)
1 kit com raps 1.4 + arduino mega 2560 + 4 Driver A4988 + dissipadores R$ 80,41 (Banggood)

ATÉ AQUI TOTAL DE 636,70 o desenho da estrutura foi elaborado para o motor nema 17 porém os preços deles mudam de acordo com a força, eu usei os de 4,7 Kg/f
mas não é necessário tudo isso, escolhendo motores mais fracos fica ainda mais barato.

O projeto original antes de todas as alterações que fiz era menor e utilizava um motor mais simples, eu até consegui fazer
funcionar mas não foi muito satisfatório, e com base no projeto desse rapaz eu criei o meu do zero.

link do projeto original: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCANTu2DwiGg0YkQu_2aPpNA/videos

A estrutura pode ser feita em madeira que sairá bem mais barata porém qualquer erro em corte e furo pode fazer diferença, 
por isso eu levei em uma empresa e fiz o corte em máquina CNC de acrílico de 3mm para as peças de mesas e de 10mm para a base.

Pra mim saiu R$ 150,00 todas as peças cortadas em acrílico.

Comprei uma caixa de ferramentas opcional para ficar estéticamente melhor.

CONFIGURAÇÃO DO ARDUÍNO QUE USO ATUALMENTE NA MINHA IMPRESSORA, NO MARLIN.

// Mechanical endstop with COM to ground and NC to Signal uses "false" here (most common setup).
#define X_MIN_ENDSTOP_INVERTING true // set to true to invert the logic of the endstop.
#define Y_MIN_ENDSTOP_INVERTING true // set to true to invert the logic of the endstop.
#define Z_MIN_ENDSTOP_INVERTING true // set to true to invert the logic of the endstop.
#define X_MAX_ENDSTOP_INVERTING false // set to true to invert the logic of the endstop.
#define Y_MAX_ENDSTOP_INVERTING false // set to true to invert the logic of the endstop.
#define Z_MAX_ENDSTOP_INVERTING false // set to true to invert the logic of the endstop.
#define Z_MIN_PROBE_ENDSTOP_INVERTING false // set to true to invert the logic of the endstop.


// Invert the stepper direction. Change (or reverse the motor connector) if an axis goes the wrong way.
#define INVERT_X_DIR false
#define INVERT_Y_DIR false
#define INVERT_Z_DIR false

// @section extruder

// For direct drive extruder v9 set to true, for geared extruder set to false.
#define INVERT_E0_DIR true
#define INVERT_E1_DIR false
#define INVERT_E2_DIR false
#define INVERT_E3_DIR false

// default settings

#define DEFAULT_AXIS_STEPS_PER_UNIT   {80, 80, 199.004, 142.85} // X, Y, Z and E
#define DEFAULT_MAX_FEEDRATE          {300, 300, 50, 25}   // (mm/sec)
#define DEFAULT_MAX_ACCELERATION      {3000, 3000, 100, 10000}   //  X, Y, Z, E maximum start speed for accelerated moves. E default values are good for Skeinforge 40+, for older versions raise them a lot.

#define DEFAULT_ACCELERATION          3000   // X, Y, Z and E acceleration in mm/s^2 for printing moves
#define DEFAULT_RETRACT_ACCELERATION  8000      // E acceleration in mm/s^2 for retracts
#define DEFAULT_TRAVEL_ACCELERATION   3000    // X, Y, Z acceleration in mm/s^2 for travel (non printing) moves

// The speed change that does not require acceleration (i.e. the software might assume it can be done instantaneously)
#define DEFAULT_XYJERK                20.0    // (mm/sec)
#define DEFAULT_ZJERK                 0.4     // (mm/sec)
#define DEFAULT_EJERK                 5.0    // (mm/sec)

title: Large scale DIY 3D printer - 1200 x 1200mm print bed - Build progress and test print preview
description:
Design download, and more information can be found at:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1977727

You can also check us out on Facebook:
https://www.facebook.com/Sub33D/

Filament for the printer is created on our own modified Lyman / Mulier version 5 Filament Extruder:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RwAdB6rVrKg

This printer was designed to print very large scale using recycled ABS plastic (we also recycle, shred and produce recycled ABS filament).
Most of the other very large scale printers out there tend to print in PLA which is a lot less problematic at large scale.

Main features:
- Build volume 1200mm x 1200mm x 600mm
- H bot layout with fixed heat-bed (4 x z-axis motors to move the light weight H frame rather than the insanely heavy heat-bed)
- 1mm nozzle, double volcano extruder hot end to increase flow rate (80W total heater power)
- 2400W heatbed using 4 x 230V 600W 400mm x 400mm silicone heating pads (controlled with 25A solid state relay)
- 2 x Recycled Nema23 stepper motors for y-axis, driven by single 5A CNC type stepper driver
- 4 x Recycled Nema23 stepper motors for z-axis, driven by single 5A CNC type stepper driver
- 1 x Recycled Nema23 stepper motor for x-axis, driven by standard 2.5A stepper driver
- 1 x Recycled Nema17 stepper motor for extruder, driven by standard 2.5A stepper driver
- Designed in Sketchup Make 2017, design file included in thingiverse link downloads (Sub33D v3.07.09.skp)
- Frame built from 50mm x 50mm x 2mm box section aluminium
- Total build cost is close to $2000 AUD
- Marlin-RC firmware also included in thingiverse link downloads (Marlin-RC.zip)

If anyone is thinking to build something like this I would recommend using a 12mm heat-bed plate (rather than 6mm) as the aluminium plate deforms up to 5mm when heated to 90 deg C, I am using 9 x 9 point auto-bed leveling to pick up the deformation shape).
Also the 400mm x 400m 600W silicone heaters are a little small as the distance between them causes around a 10 deg C difference on the heat-bed surface between the heaters and above them).
I'm Currently fitting 4 x 150W IR heaters to reduce heat-bed deformation and maintain consistent heat on printed ABS parts.

Special thanks to Substation33 for all the support and recycled materials.

title: Construção de Impressora 3D em casa, Episódio 2
description:
Atenção, esses vídeos demonstrativos são apenas uma amostra do que eu (Patola, o cara que não aparece nesse vídeo!) ensino nas aulas de Ensino À Distância (EAD) da Techtraining! Faça o curso inteiro e aprenda BEM mais que isso. :-) http://www.techtraining.eng.br ou agende uma palestra se quiser conhecer nosso trabalho.

Desculpe, pessoal! Tentei fazer um vídeo de 5 minutos mas não teve jeito, a montagem do quadro é meio longa e mesmo assim ainda não terminamos, deu 12 minutos e meio com câmera acelerada.

Dá um pouco de trabalho mesmo montar uma graber, e olha que ela é uma das impressoras 3D mais fáceis de construir. Não quer ter trabalho, mas gosta do jeitão dela? Pense se não vale a pena adquirir uma impressora da Sethi3D, a AiP A3. Além de muitas melhorias, reforços e seguranças em relação à graber original, ela tem a CPU Sethi com proteção contra descargas, LCD com cartão SD, garantia e suporte: http://www.sethi3d.com.br/produto/impressora-sethi3d-aip.html

Ou, se você ainda prefere montar para ter aprendizado e um preço (bem) mais barato, pode comprar a versão em kit e com manual aqui: http://www.sethi3d.com.br/produto/kit-de-montagem-sethi3d-aip.html

Ah, se seu negócio é grande volume de impressão? Veja se a Sethi BB não atenderia a suas demandas: http://www.sethi3d.com.br/impressora-sethi3d-bb-175mm

Neste episódio tratamos da primeira parte de montagem do quadro. Como existem algumas variedades diferentes de corte da graber por aí (algo típico de projetos open-source), procuramos citar os que conhecemos e suas diferenças, mesmo tendo que escolher um pra usar.

Em especial, agradecemos ao Valter F.C., Alex Borro e Miguel d'Ávila por suas contribuições. A lista de materiais completa da graber você encontra aqui: http://graberi3.blogspot.com.br/2013/11/graber-i3-lista-de-pecas-e-vitaminas.html#more

No vídeo usamos certos comprimentos de barras lisas que é equivalente ao comprimento máximo da lista de materiais. Fazemos isso porque vamos medir depois de montada e então cortar o excesso do tamanho certo. Se você não consegue acesso a nenhuma ferramenta que corte aço, pode ser preferível encomendar o comprimento mínimo.

Uma empresa que pode fazer esse corte de barras lisas é a marvitubos, que atende por email e tem website. Peça barras lisas cromadas de 8 mm de diâmetro.

Os links do modelo 3D dos adaptadores de porcas M3 desse vídeo são esses (qualquer um deles serve, imprima um para cada porca M3 que for usar):

http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:167206
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:285311
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:341215

Um dos Pillow Blocks impressos que podem ser usados com o suporte da mesa, se você não quiser usar as pecinhas de MDF, é esse: 

http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:228725

Os parafusos, porcas e demais "vitaminas" (peças não-impressas) que usamos neste vídeo são:

6 parafusos M3x12 ou M4x10 (o corte permite ambos, mas aconselhamos o M3x12)
6 porcas M3 com adaptadores impressos (se você usar o M3x12) ou M4 sem adaptadores (se usar o M4x10)
6 arruelas M4 (mesmo se usar parafuso M3x12)
22 parafusos M3x16
26 porcas M3 com adaptadores impressos (é bom imprimir ou comprar pelo menos uns 50 adaptadores desses pois alguns podem quebrar durante a montagem)
2 parafusos M3x20
2 parafusos M3x25
12 parafusos M3x35
12 porcas auto-travantes M3 (porcas M3 comuns, sem adaptadores impressos, podem ser usadas, mas tenderão mais a escapar)

3 rolamentos LM8UU (rolamentos lineares com furo de 8 mm)

Nenhum animal foi ferido durante a confecção desse vídeo (mas alguns gatinhos foram afagados) e, mais importante, nenhum SOFTWARE PROPRIETÁRIO foi utilizado para o mesmo. Utilizamos:

- GNU/Linux como sistema operacional;
- GIMP para edição de imagens de bitmap;
- Inkscape para edição de imagens vetoriais;
- Blender para os efeitos tridimensionais;
- Audacity para edição de áudio;
- kdenlive para a edição do vídeo;
- Mozilla Firefox (sem flash player) para upload do vídeo para o youtube;
- gvim para anotações de texto;
- yakuake + zsh para acompanhamento da renderização pelo terminal :P

As músicas, jingles e efeitos são de um pacote gratuito disponibilizado num episódio especial do excelente canal "Manual do Mundo".

title: Nicer Screw Thread In SketchUp ( 3D Printable + Nut Thread ) 2020 Update notice
description:
Important notice 2020!:  Helix14.rbz has disappeared from the web! But you can use : http://sketchucation.com/plugin/1379-helix_along_curve
You can get it when you FREE! subscribe to sketchucation.com. Draw a line along blue axis, select it and draw, helix along curve. There is no pitch, so you have calculate like 150mm (line) / 5 laps = pitch 30mm. And sections per lap 96 in this case.



This technique allows you to make flat crest and root for the thread. Also, the thread is solid, no holes. On this video closely imitating coarse M24. M24 really has a little bit different dimensions and the root is double width of the crest and usually rounded. Anyway  for some 3D printing projects not so necessary. 

You need only the helix plug-in. The Solid Inspector & the CleanUp3 plug-ins make things easier when drawing more than the just the thread. I drew the outer thread "by hand" because the Boolean plugin crashed.

Draw a shank with some degree angle to the end of the bolt and you get a chamfer for the nut part.

The model was 3D printed nicely on Reprap Prusa i3 FDM printer.

title: ANET A8 Plus Assembly Guide, Setup, Review, Easy Upgrades (STLs Included). Is This Printer Worth It?
description:
The ANET A8 Plus is an entry level printer and its smaller predecessor, the A8, had been based on the Prusa i3 machines. The A8 plus adds volume with a build size of 300mm x 300mm x 350mm which is quite generous considering the low cost of this machine. 

The frame is an all metal extrusion construction making it very stable and stiff. It comes with a direct drive extruder, heated print bed, and simple LCD screen. 

Overall this kit is fairly simple to assemble, however, it will take you some time to do. Pay close attention to the details while assembling to get the most of out of your printer later. Also, keep a close watch on the quality of parts as you are likely to get some sub-par quality parts in a kit with a price this low. Don't expect a turn key printer out of the box, and do expect to have to get creative at times.

My biggest complaints about this machine is the lack of strain relief, no wire management, and lack of grommets for wires passing through metal enclosures. The heated bed connector and cable is also inadequate for the application. I would be happy to pay more for a printer that addresses these issues. I have tried to rectify some of these problems with my own design files that you can find here:

► https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4929130

That being said, this printer prints surprisingly well if you take good care in setting it up properly. The direct drive extruder meters filament well, and small details come out sharp in fine prints. The simplicity of the machine makes it a good candidate for fun and simple future upgrades and would be a good platform to build your knowledge of 3D printing. 

I did not include slicer settings in this video but you should be able to find slicer profiles for A8 machines online quite easily. It is a very popular platform. You can also start with other generic printer profiles from other popular machines like the Creality machines. Select a Creality machine with a direct drive extruder and get that slicer profile... adjust the printer dimensions and you should have something that works nicely.

I would recommend this machine for beginners and advanced users alike. In either case you would be looking for a hobby printer and a project, not a ready to use tool. If you are looking for a more straightforward experience in getting printing, I would suggest the ANET ET5X as it is much easier to assemble and the print quality is also good. The overall machine is more well thought out than the A8 and is only slightly more expensive. 

ANET A8 Plus. As an Amazon Associate I earn from qualifying purchases (at no extra cost to you):
https://amzn.to/3PP71Bk

If you have any questions about the assembly, the printer, etc, please post your comments in the comment section down below. I try and get back to everyone. 

Thanks for watching!

title: Cómo desplegar tu proyecto Laravel en Digital Ocean
description:
En este curso veremos como desplegar tu proyecto Laravel y como programar tareas para que se ejecuten cada vez que hagas un deploy. Estas tareas pueden ser, ejecutar las migraciones, actualizar las dependencias de composer, compilar nuevamente los assets, etc.
También haremos las configuraciones necesarias para que ocurra un nuevo deploy cada vez que actualicemos nuestro repositorio de github.
En el curso no usaremos intermediarios como Laravel Forge, sino que instalaremos y configuraremos nosotros mismos nuestro servidor.

Link: https://bit.ly/3Udn9PG

title: Build a Blog with Laravel [8,9] #0 - Introduction
description:
Laravel is one of the most popular frameworks to create a variety of websites. You can create portfolio websites, admin dashboards, e-commerce websites, and more. Most importantly, you can create blogs with Laravel. This, however, would require setting up a database and an admin dashboard to be able to enter the posts and their content and then display them.
In this series, you will learn how to create a blog with Laravel.

Recently, the Laravel 9 version has been launched. In this video, we will take some simple steps to install Laravel 9 on Windows. We need to make sure that our server meets the Laravel 9 requirements.

To Install Laravel 9, you can install Xampp then Composer and finally install Laravel 9.

Click  Download Composer from www.getcomposer.org: 
https://getcomposer.org/download/

Click here to download git:
https://git-scm.com/downloads

Click here to download Visual Studio Code:
https://code.visualstudio.com/download

title: How to tune your slicer settings featuring Ender 3 - UPDATE IN DESCRIPTION
description:
UPDATE: This video is quite old now and I've since created a completely free and open source website that allows you to generate calibration tests like this for ANY 3D printer: https://teachingtechyt.github.io/index.html
Details here: https://youtu.be/9kDK7czgMxc

I get frequent requests for slicing profiles, so I’d thought it might be worth a video showing ways you can take a profile and tweak it for better results.

This video covers extruder calibration, flow rate/extrusion multiplier calibration, temperature, speed and retraction calibration. If you have an Ender 3 you can download and run the g-code from the link below. Most others printers can do the same, assuming they don’t have a really small bed.

Edit: As several have pointed out, my speed conversion was wrong. The speed test goes from 3000 to 6000 mm / min, which is 50 mm/sec to 100 mm/sec every 5 mm. The outline is slowed by 50%, hence the need to slice it hollow so you can see the full speed on the inside walls.

Edit2: Clever people have pointed out that a minimum layer time setting was preventing the speed test gcode from running properly. The gcode has now been updated in the Thingiverse link.

I've also added my FFF file for Simplify3D.

title: How To Install a Bootloader on the Anet A8 3D Printer
description:
Some Anet A8 3D printers may ship without a bootloader on board, making it difficult to install firmware updates. If this describes your printer, you may wonder: can you install a bootloader using a Mac? Yes, of course you can. Let me show you how.

*NOTE*
Installing a bootloader erases the existing firmware on your 3D printer. After installing a bootloader, you must then install firmware. Follow one of these videos to do it. If the video covering the firmware you want to install is not ready yet, please wait to do this installation.

FIRMWARE INSTALLATION VIDEO LINKS:
Install factory firmware on the Anet A8 3D Printer: https://youtu.be/1lnST6WgdVw
Install Marlin 1.1.9 firmware on the Anet A8 3D Printer: https://youtu.be/V7_zIQALk6E
Install Klipper firmware on the Anet A8 3D Printer: https://youtu.be/EX8dJkdcmJQ

Huge thanks to Mark Corliss (Corliss Media 2.0) for generously covering the cost of the Anet A8 used in this episode. We'll be using it in a series of episodes where we install the Klipper firmware, and the first step is making sure we have a bootloader on board!

HARDWARE AND SOFTWARE LINKS:
USBasp AVR Programmer Device
• https://amzn.to/2XrWiG3 [Affiliate Link]

10Pin to 6Pin Adapter Board
• https://amzn.to/2xESvGd [Affiliate Link]

USB Extension Cable (Optional, if you need the extra reach)
• https://amzn.to/2RWQUEL [Affiliate Link]

Arduino IDE for Mac
• https://www.arduino.cc/download_handler.php?f=/arduino-1.8.8-macosx.zip

SkyNet3D anet-board Definition File
• https://github.com/SkyNet3D/anet-board

Klipper Firmware:
• https://bit.ly/2sgoaeh
The Klipper project is 3d-printer firmware. There are two parts to this firmware - code that runs on a micro-controller and code that runs on a host machine. The host software does the work to build a schedule of events, while the micro-controller software does the work to execute the provided schedule at the specified times.

title: How To 3D Print Holographic Effect- With Any 3D Printer!!
description:
In this video I will quickly show you how you can create a holographic finish effect on your 3D prints. All you need is a 3D printer and a diffraction grating sheet -  the specs of the one I used are 13,500 Lines/inch. I got mine from Amazon. They have several patterns available to choose from as well. Simply tape the film to the bed of your 3D printer and any surface of your 3D print will achieve the holographic effect. There are a few videos out there explaining the process more in depth but I just thought I'd share my experience with it. 

How many times will it work? I'm not sure how many prints you can get before the film starts to wear down- comment below if you happen to have had more experience and would like to share. My guess is 10-20 quality uses before quality degrades. 

If you found this video useful, like the video and I'll try and create more content like it. Thanks for watching!

title: Learn Blender for a CAD User - Part 1 - Simple Example in Fusion and Blender 3.0 #Fusion360 #Blender
description:
In this video we are going to kick of a new series where we learn Blender modeling in Blender 3.0.  Over the years I have tried to learn Blender a few times by following tutorials and it just never seemed to stick to the point where I could recreate the project without the videos.  So through my experience learning Blender "my way" I wanted to pass on the approach of a user who knows CAD, specifically Fusion 360, and try to draw some common workflows between the two.

In this video we are going to talk about Parametric CAD, Modeling styles and then create a simple Form body in Fusion, and repeat the process in Blender.  We are going to work in Blender without any shortcut keys and we will take it extremely slow. 

For this series I plan to take the time to really dive into certain tools, play with them before we tackle a project.  I don't know what that project is yet but it will be an attainable goal.

Before you get started you should have Fusion 360 and Blender installed and ready to go.  Blender is free and open source and you can download it here: https://www.blender.org/download/releases/3-0/

Fusion 360 has a Hobby license as well as a Commercial license.  For what we are doing the Hobby license will work just fine.  You can download a 30 day trial of Fusion 360 here: https://www.autodesk.com/products/fusion-360/free-trial

The end goal is to make you comfortable with Blender so you can tackle more complex projects without being overwhelmed.  Some Youtube 

Channels that I think do a great job with Blender:

https://www.youtube.com/c/CGGeek - Unique style very knowledgable
https://www.youtube.com/c/BlenderGuruOfficial - Tons of content good flow
https://www.youtube.com/c/TheCGEssentials  -also has a fusion channel that seems to be geared to woodworking
https://www.youtube.com/c/GrantAbbitt - overall great pace and info
https://www.youtube.com/c/DECODEDVFX  - High level rendering and animation

title: Como criar seu primeiro app híbrido, usando Ionic e Angular
description:
Nos dias atuais para quase tudo que fazemos em nosso dia a dia temos um app, mas também temos vários sistemas operacionais como Android, IOS, Windows, etc. e isso se torna um problema quando a questão é app nativo, ou seja um app dedicado para Android por exemplo. Para que o desenvolvedor nao tenha de aprender todas as tecnologias dedicadas para cada sistema operacional, o Ionic entra para resolver esse problema. O desenvolvedor escolhe um framework JS que conhece e desenvolve todo porjeto em cima dele, e na hora de compilar os apps para os sistemas operacionais, o Ionic se encarrega dessa tarefa, dando a possibilidade de criar um site PWA também.   

Neste vídeo tutorial, vou mostrar como voce pode criar seu primeiro app hibrido usando o Ionic e o framework javascript angular.

title: Laravel DDD - Estrutura de pastas e arquivos - DDD Domain Driven Design #001
description:
Atuamos com Laravel faz mais de 5 anos e sabemos o quão difícil é encontrar conteúdo estruturado e completo na nossa língua nativa (português): deep dive, performance, API's, testes automatizados, deploy. Pensando nisso, estamos desenvolvendo uma formação completa em Laravel, algo que não existe no mercado nacional.

Quer fazer parte da lista de interessados na nossa formação em Laravel? 
Se inscreve no forms abaixo:

https://forms.gle/QcETxJ7jWhrw72VT8
Deixe sua sugestão de conteúdo: https://bit.ly/BeerAndCodeSugestao

Hoje inicia o nosso Curso completo de Domain Driven Design, conhecido também por DDD. Nessa primeira aula, vamos te ensinar a estruturar do zero a sua aplicação Laravel para iniciar nesse novo conceito.

title: Full PHP 8 Tutorial - Learn PHP The Right Way In 2022/2023
description:
If you want to learn PHP the right way, then you are in the right place. In this course, you will learn PHP from beginners level all the way to advanced. The "right way" is subjective of course, but my goal is to teach PHP the way I would want to learn myself where important topics like security, caching, performance, configuration, routing, dependency management, dependency injection & testing are not omitted even when the course is for beginners. This course will not be only for beginners even though it will be beginner-friendly in the beginning. The course will be split into three sections. Each video will have a lot of details about the topic so even if you already know that topic I recommend watching it since you might learn something new.

This is the first video & it is an introduction to the course. I talk about what PHP is, why you should use it, how it works, and the overview of the course's main topics.

title: How To Install PHP & What Are Web Servers - PHP 8 Tutorial
description:
Let's set up the local development environment. We need PHP, a Web Server, MySQL & Code Editor. There are many ways one could install these, you could do it manually, you can use "all in one solution" like XAMPP / MAMP / WAMP or you could use a better alternative like virtual machines or Docker. In this video, I will be showing you how to get PHP up and running using XAMPP but in the second section, we will use Docker. In addition to setting up the local environment, you will learn what a webserver is & how it works.

title: PHP Return, Declare & Tickable Statements - Full PHP 8 Tutorial
description:
In this PHP tutorial, you will learn about the declare & return statements. When the return is used within a function it stops the execution of the function & returns the value of the expression it's given, if no expression is given it will return null. If the return is used in the global scope (out of a function) then the execution of that script will end & will return the value of the expression or null if no expression is given. Declare statement is used to set execution directives, there are three directives: ticks directive, encoding directive & strict_types directive. 

The reason I did not talk about the goto statement is that it just makes code harder to maintain & read. You can use other control structures to achieve the same result. If you still want to know how to use it, here is the link to the docs: https://www.php.net/manual/en/control-structures.goto.php

title: How To Work With PHPs Configuration File - PHP.INI - Full PHP 8 Tutorial
description:
In this PHP tutorial, you will learn what the PHP configuration file is, what are some of the important settings & how to change them. The php.ini file is the settings or the configuration file for your PHP, each version can have its own php.ini. This file allows you to control how certain things in PHP work. You are able to also change some of the configuration settings at runtime by using ini_set.

title: Basic Apache Webserver Configuration & Virtual Hosts - Full PHP 8 Tutorial
description:
In this PHP tutorial, you will learn the basics of apache configuration files & how to work with them. You will also learn how to rewrite URLs using .htaccess files & the difference between .htaccess & httpd.conf files and why you should not use .htaccess files.

NOTE
At 13:20 I copied htaccess content into vhosts config, if it does not work for you or you are setting rewrite rules globally then try the following instead:

RewriteCond %{LA-U:REQUEST_FILENAME} !-f
RewriteCond %{LA-U:REQUEST_FILENAME} !-d

The reason for it is because LA-U (look-ahead URL based) is needed for the proper value of REQUEST_FILENAME in some cases. More info on it can be read on https://httpd.apache.org/docs/current/mod/mod_rewrite.html (search for LA-U)

title: Mini Exercise Project Overview - Full PHP 8 Tutorial
description:
We've reached the end of the first section of the course. Finally! This means that now we get to move on to more fun topics & actually work on a project. It may not seem so but we actually covered a lot of topics in this first section & there are a lot more tutorials/lessons on the way. There is a small exercise project that I will implement in the next video using things that we've learned so far. The project that we'll be working on is going to be a simple budgeting/expense tracking application, but because we have not covered all the necessary things to implement this now we will slowly add on features as I cover the related topics. We will start with a simple file parser that reads one or multiply CSV files & extracts transactions from them.

I really hope you enjoyed the first section of the course, please do let me know what you thought about it or if you have any kind of feedback. title: Static Properties & Methods In Object Oriented PHP -  Full PHP 8 Tutorial
description:
In the first section of the course, you learned about variable scopes & static variables. In this lesson, you will learn about static properties & methods of the class with some use cases including singleton & factory design patterns. There are few differences between static properties & non-static properties, one is that static properties are associated & belong to the class itself & not to any particular object, while non-static properties are associated & belong to the object. So when you create an object, that object gets fresh values for the non-static properties. Another difference is that you need to use the dollar sign when accessing static properties, unlike regular properties where you don't use the dollar sign to access non-static properties.

title: PHP Anonymous Classes - Full PHP 8 Tutorial
description:
In this lesson, you will learn what anonymous classes are in PHP, how to create & use them. Anonymous classes like anonymous functions are nameless. You are able to create one-off objects using anonymous classes. You can either assign an anonymous class to a variable that will simply give you the object of that anonymous class, or just pass it as an argument since it's just an expression.

Note that at 4:54 I copied constructor promoted properties & pasted them into the anonymous class. Promoted properties should not be used inside an anonymous class when you are extending from a base class since those already exist on the base class.

title: PHP Iterators & Iterable Type - Iterate Over Objects - Full PHP 8 Tutorial
description:
In this lesson, you will learn what iterators are & how to work with them in PHP. It may sound scary but it's actually pretty simple. With iterators you can define how you want your objects to be iterated on, by default when you iterate over objects in PHP it will iterate on visible properties on the object but sometimes you may want to iterate on a specific property of the object instead. Learn what Iterator, IteratorAggregate & Traversable interfaces are, what iterable data type is & how to implement a basic collection pattern that you might be familiar with from frameworks like Laravel.

title: PHP PDO Tutorial Part 1 - Prepared Statements - SQL Injection - Full PHP 8 Tutorial
description:
In this lesson, you will learn how to connect to the database from PHP using PHP Data Objects or in short PDO. PDO provides data access layer abstraction where common methods can be used to interact with different databases like MySQL, SQLite, and so on. You will learn about prepared statements, what SQL injection is & how it works, how to prevent SQL injection, learn about the difference between binding params by value or by reference, the difference between placeholders & named parameters, emulated prepares & so on.

NOTE: If you have concerns/questions about 15:28 please watch the beginning of Part 2 of the PDO lesson, I address & explain there. This is just a debug query & to save an extra line I decided to pass an integer directly to the query. I don't recommend you do that, even though this particular example has no SQL Injection vulnerability, someone might make a mistake & introduce the vulnerability. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e6yLUvpcOZo
